{
  "Answer": {
    "Title": "Optimizing Dockerfile with Layer Caching for pip install",
    "Explanation": [
      "The problem is that `COPY . /app` copies all source files before `pip install` runs. Any change to any source file invalidates the Docker layer cache at that point, forcing pip install to re-run even if requirements.txt hasn't changed.",
      "",
      "The fix is to separate the dependency installation into its own cacheable layer by:",
      "1. First copying ONLY `requirements.txt` into the image.",
      "2. Running `pip install` immediately after — this layer is now cached and only invalidated when `requirements.txt` itself changes.",
      "3. Then copying the rest of the application source code in a subsequent step.",
      "",
      "This way, Docker's layer cache preserves the `pip install` result across builds as long as `requirements.txt` is unchanged. Only a modification to `requirements.txt` will trigger a fresh install. Regular source code edits (e.g., changes to `main.py`) only invalidate the later `COPY . /app` layer, making rebuilds much faster."
    ],
    "ActualAnswer": [
      "FROM python:3.11",
      "WORKDIR /app",
      "COPY requirements.txt .",
      "RUN pip install -r requirements.txt",
      "COPY . .",
      "CMD [\"python\", \"main.py\"]"
    ],
    "ExpectedAnswer": [
      [
        "FROM python:3.11",
        "WORKDIR /app",
        "COPY requirements.txt .",
        "RUN pip install -r requirements.txt",
        "COPY . .",
        "CMD [\"python\", \"main.py\"]"
      ]
    ],
