    "Title": "CircleCI Pipeline Minimum Wall-Clock Time",
    "Explanation": [
      "To find the minimum wall-clock time for the full pipeline, we need to calculate the critical path, which is the longest sequence of dependent jobs. The pipeline execution unfolds as follows:",
      "",
      "1. `checkout` runs first since it has no dependencies. It takes 10s. (Total elapsed time: 10s)",
      "2. `install` runs next, waiting for `checkout`. It takes 45s. (Total elapsed time: 10s + 45s = 55s)",
      "3. After `install` finishes, `lint`, `test-unit`, and `test-integration` all start simultaneously and run in parallel. ",
      "   - `lint` takes 20s (Finishes at 55s + 20s = 75s)",
      "   - `test-unit` takes 90s (Finishes at 55s + 90s = 145s)",
      "   - `test-integration` takes 120s (Finishes at 55s + 120s = 175s)",
      "4. `build` must wait for all three of these jobs to finish. The longest of the three is `test-integration`, taking 120s. Thus, `build` can only start at the 175s mark. It takes 30s. (Total elapsed time: 175s + 30s = 205s)",
      "5. Finally, `deploy` waits for `build` to finish and takes 15s. (Total elapsed time: 205s + 15s = 220s)",
      "",
      "The critical path length is the sum of the times of `checkout`, `install`, `test-integration`, `build`, and `deploy`: 10 + 45 + 120 + 30 + 15 = 220 seconds."
